==English==
===Alternative spellings===
* [[syke]]

===Etymology 1===
From the northern form of Old English ''[[sic#Old English|sīċ]]'' (see ''[[sitch]]''), from Germanic.  Cognate with Norwegian ''[[sik]]''.

====Noun====
{{en-noun-reg}}

# A [[gutter]] or [[ditch]]; a small [[stream]] that frequently dries up in the summer.

===Etymology 2===
Variant of ''[[siche]]''.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|sikes|siking|siked}} 

# {{archaic}} To [[sigh]] or [[sob]].
#*'''Late C14''': For his absence wepeth she and '''siketh''' — Geoffrey Chaucer, ‘The Franklin's Tale’, ''Canterbury Tales''

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{archaic}} A [[sigh]].

